{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518479"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12927"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12927"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.07,0.02,0.8,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40673"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2921"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43900"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of generalised abdominal pain, anorexia, and vomiting. He has never had symptoms like this before. He has a medical history of polycystic kidney disease (PKD) but is otherwise in good health. His PKD is managed with dietary salt restriction, increased fluid intake, captopril and tolvaptan. His most recent eGFR was 63 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 122/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft but tender in the right upper quadrant, with a palpable mass. His liver span is 15 cm, and his kidneys are ballotable. A bedside ultrasound shows free fluid in the right upper quadrant and suprapubic areas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute cholecystitis","Acute hepatitis","Appendicitis","Hepatic cyst rupture","Small bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with polycystic kidney disease (PKD) is most likely experiencing a complication related to his condition. PKD is an autosomal dominant genetic disorder characterised by the formation of fluid-filled cysts in the kidneys and extrarenal sites, particularly the liver. The patient\u0027s presentation with acute abdominal pain, a palpable mass in the right upper quadrant, and free intraperitoneal fluid on ultrasound is highly suggestive of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatic cyst rupture\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E could present with right upper quadrant pain and tenderness, but the presence of free intraperitoneal fluid would be unusual. Additionally, a bedside ultrasound would likely reveal gallstones if present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting, but other characteristic symptoms such as jaundice, scleral icterus, and dark urine are absent in this case. Free intraperitoneal fluid would also be an uncommon finding in acute hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E is always a consideration in cases of acute abdominal pain. However, the location of pain and tenderness in the right upper quadrant, rather than the right lower quadrant, makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E can present with abdominal pain and vomiting, and an abdominal mass could be involved in such a process. However, the ultrasound findings of free fluid in the right upper quadrant and suprapubic areas are not typical for small bowel obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatic cysts are a common extrarenal manifestation of PKD. These cysts can lead to complications such as bleeding (either into the cyst itself or into the abdominal cavity), infection, or rupture. In this case, the sudden onset of symptoms, the presence of a palpable mass in the right upper quadrant, and the finding of free intraperitoneal fluid on ultrasound all point towards a ruptured hepatic cyst as the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In a patient with polycystic kidney disease presenting with right upper quadrant pain, nausea, vomiting, and free intraperitoneal fluid, consider ruptured hepatic cyst as a diagnosis.","Hepatic cysts are a common extrarenal manifestation of polycystic kidney disease and can lead to complications such as bleeding, infection, or rupture."],"references":["Luciano RL, Dahl NK. Extra-renal manifestations of autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD): considerations for routine screening and management. Nephrol Dial Transplant. 2014 Feb;29(2):247-54. Available at:  https://doi.org/10.1093/ndt/gft437","Qian Q, King BF, Kamath PS, et al. Clinical Profile of Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Liver Disease. Hepatology 2003; 37:164-71. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12500201/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40673"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12927"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40673"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T21:01:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T21:05:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5365"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},